ribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":66,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Blount was born about 1149, in Saxlingham, Norfolk, England as the son of Sir William le Blount - Second Lord of Saxlingham. He married Anceline Blount about 1174, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died after 1216."},"et":{"Abt 1149–Aft 1216":"umbes 1149–pärast 1216","1149–1216":"1149–1216","1154–1180":"1154–1180","1170–1245":"1170–1245","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","1216":"1216","1215":"1215","1149":"1149","Aft 1216":"pärast 1216","1245":"1245","1154":"1154","Abt 1149":"umbes 1149","1120":"1120","1170":"1170","about 1174":"umbes 1174","1180":"1180",", , , Deutschland":"Saksamaa","Saxlingham, No